To normalize the text in Rust, you can use the `trim()` function to remove leading and trailing whitespace and then split the string into words using the whitespace as a separator, filtering out any empty strings that might result from consecutive spaces. Then, you can join the words back into a single string with a single space separating them.

Here's an example of how you can do it in Rust:

```rust
let text = "   ONLY generate RUST Code (no fn main function) and nothing else   Normalize the following text using Rust.the     Cat    in  the  hat      ";

let normalized_text = text.trim()
                          .split_whitespace()
                          .collect::<Vec<&str>>()
                          .join(" ");
```
